Dataset

This dataset comes from Spotify’s API on all albums listed on Spotify for Taylor Swift. It was complied by Kaggle.com user Jarred Priester. (link: https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/jarredpriester/taylor-swift-spotify-dataset) It includes 582 entries that breakdown 363 of Taylor Swift’s songs by name, album, danceability, energy, tempo, valence, and popularity, among other information. This project aims to use this data to create a model that predicts the popularity of a song when given values for the other variables.

Upload data and removed columns irrelevant to this analysis such as release date, track number, song id, ect.

taylor_swift_spotify <- read_excel("taylor_swift_spotify.xlsx")
taylor_grouped <- taylor_swift_spotify[c(1, 7:17)]

Simplify the data by grouping together all of the songs that have the same name, as many of the songs are duplicates as they appear in multiple albums.

taylor_grouped %>% 
  group_by(name) %>% 
  tally(n ='num_duplicates')
taylor_final <- taylor_grouped %>% 
  group_by(name) %>% summarize(acousticness = mean(acousticness), 
  danceability = mean(danceability), energy = mean(energy), liveness = mean(liveness), 
  loudness = mean(loudness), speechiness = mean(speechiness), tempo = mean(tempo), 
  valence = mean(valence), popularity = mean(popularity), duration_ms = mean(duration_ms))
  taylor_final %>%
    head(n=5)

Data Model

Fit a Bayesian generalized linear model, with popularity as the response variable.

as.data.frame(taylor_final)
taylor_model <- stan_glm(
  popularity ~ acousticness + danceability + energy + liveness + loudness + speechiness + tempo + valence,
  family = gaussian(), data = taylor_final,
  prior_intercept = normal(50,20),
  prior= normal(0, 1, autoscale=TRUE),
  prior_aux= exponential(1, autoscale= TRUE),
  chains= 4, iter= 5000*2, seed= 84735)

Without looking at the data, I would assume the average song has a popularity score of 50, and popularity ranges from 10 to 90. Thus, the prior used for the intercept is (50,20).

The MCMC will run with 4 chains of 10,000 iterations to increase the liklihood that it will be sufficiently mixed.

Model Adequacy Checking

Run trace and autocorrelation plots to ensure the posterior simulation has sufficiently mixed and stabilized.

mcmc_trace(taylor_model, size= 0.3)

mcmc_dens_overlay(taylor_model)

mcmc_acf(taylor_model)

rhat(taylor_model)

##  speechiness        tempo      valence        sigma

neff_ratio(taylor_model)

##      1.01305      0.95645      0.97200      0.92110      1.29250      1.03355 
##  speechiness        tempo      valence        sigma 
##      1.18335      1.36770      0.97190      1.42060

The values of r-hat are very close to 1, so the parallel chains are consistent. The values of the effective sample size ratio are close to 1 and are higher than .1, which shows the chains are quality.

taylor_final %>% 
  add_epred_draws(taylor_model, ndraws = 50) %>% ggplot(aes(x= loudness, y= popularity)) + geom_line(aes(y=.epred, group=.draw), alpha= 0.15) + geom_point(data= taylor_final, size= 0.3)

Overlaying the predicted popularity over the observed popularity shows that the model’s predictions align well with the observed data.

pp_check(taylor_model)

The visual posterior predictive check suggests that the model captures the general center and spread of popularity fairly well, but fails to capture the multimodality of the data.

Estimation of Regression Coefficients

posterior_interval(taylor_model, prob= 0.90)
##                       5%         95%
## (Intercept)   29.1013548  59.5348318
## acousticness -11.0416709   1.4288864
## danceability  -8.4718654  17.7695786
## energy         4.7597157  30.5230151
## liveness     -36.0367659 -19.3752194
## loudness      -2.5689172  -0.9178408
## speechiness  -53.4153705 -17.9924419
## tempo         -0.0427932   0.0441502
## valence      -15.6143500   1.4262006
## sigma         13.6561440  15.4400316

When controlling for other model predictors, energy is the only variable positively associated with popularity. Liveness, loudness, and speechiness are negatively associated with popularity. Acousticness, danceablitiy, tempo, and valence are not significantly associated with popularity.

Prediction and Interpretation

This model can be used to predict the popularity of a hypothetical new Taylor Swift song.

predict_popularity <- posterior_predict(
  taylor_model, newdata = data.frame(acousticness= 0.05, danceability= 0.7, 
        energy= 0.6, liveness= 0.2, loudness= -8.5, speechiness= 0.1, tempo= 115, valence= 0.5))
mcmc_areas(predict_popularity)

Based on this model, if she created a song with 0.05 acoustiness, 0.7 danceability, 0.6 energy, 0.2 liveness, -8.5 dB loudness, 0.1 speechiness, 115 bpm tempo and 0.5 valence, the most typical popularity of the song would be about 60, and its popularity would likely range from about 50 to 70.
